  "issue_number": 2986,
  "issue_title": "Drop `colorama`",
  "issue_body": "We currently depend on [Colorama](https://github.com/tartley/colorama) on Windows, which converts ANSI formatting codes to equivalent Windows Console commands. However, on Windows >= 10, both the console host and Terminal app [support ANSI](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/Microsoft.PowerShell.Core/about/about_ansi_terminals?view=powershell-5.1#ansi-terminal-support):\n\n> On Windows 10 and higher, the Windows Console Host is [xterm](https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Xterm) compatible. The [Windows Terminal](https://www.microsoft.com/p/windows-terminal/9n0dx20hk701) application is also xterm compatible. These terminals support ANSI escape sequences.\n\n[Windows 10 reaches end of support on October 25, 2025.](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/end-of-support) We drop Python versions within 6 months of end of life, doing the same for Windows seems reasonable.\n\nThe last release of Colorama was October 24, 2022. [The year prior, they opened an issue explaining that maintenance was unlikely to move quickly, if it happened at all.](https://github.com/tartley/colorama/issues/300) This hasn't been updated since 2022 either.\n\nRemoving colorama would not break Click running on older versions of Windows. It would cause ANSI to be emitted unless `color=False` was passed to the context, which is easy enough to do if a project wants to opt-in to supporting older Windows versions.",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-24T14:30:06Z",
